    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>There Are Some Answers To Family Court Quagmire</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Committee for Modern Courts executive director Steven M Zeidman letter on September 10 article on family court problems notes alarmingly low wages paid to lawyers assigned to represent poor parents (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Families in the Balance'' (Sept. 10) raises a host of issues endemic to Family Court: crowded calendars, inadequate resources and children languishing in foster care. These problems call into question whether we lack the will to create meaningful solutions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Families in the Balance'' (Sept. 10) raises a host of issues endemic to Family Court: crowded calendars, inadequate resources and children languishing in foster care. These problems call into question whether we lack the will to create meaningful solutions.</p>
        <p>The article also flags one issue we can address: the alarmingly low wages paid to lawyers assigned to represent poor parents in Family Court. The rates -- $40 an hour for in-court work, $25 for out-of-court -- haven't changed in almost 15 years. The predictable result is an exodus of lawyers from the assigned counsel list.</p>
        <p>STEVEN M. ZEIDMAN  Executive Director,  Committee for Modern Courts</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
